{"title_page": "Hart Leavitt", "text_new": "[[File:Undergroundrailroadsmall2.jpg|thumb|Map of some Underground Railroad routes]]\n'''Hart Leavitt''' (December 19, 1809 \u2013 1881) was a Massachusetts merchant, landowner, legislator and prominent abolitionist. Leavitt was the brother of [[Roger Hooker Leavitt]], with whom he operated an [[Underground Railroad]] station in [[Charlemont, Massachusetts]], where the two brothers, aided by a third sibling in New York, the reformer and abolitionist publisher [[Joshua Leavitt]], sheltered escaped slaves on their journey northward. The Massachusetts homes of Hart Leavitt and his brother Roger Hooker are both listed today on the [[National Park Service]]'s Underground Railroad Network to Freedom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/history/ugrr/list.htm|title=National Underground Railroad Network to Freedom Listings, National Park Service, nps.gov}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nHart Leavitt was born in [[Heath, Massachusetts]] in 1809, the son of landowner and Massachusetts legislator  Roger Leavitt <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxMXAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA339|title=History and Proceedings of the Pocumtuck Valley Memorial Association|first=Pocumtuck Valley Memorial Association (Deerfield|last=Mass.)|date=October 3, 1905|publisher=The Association|via=Google Books}}</ref> and his wife Chloe (Maxwell) Leavitt, and the grandson of Charlemont's first minister, [[Congregationalist]] Rev. [[Jonathan Leavitt (minister)|Jonathan Leavitt]], who was eventually turned out by the town for his [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|Loyalist]] sentiments. Hart Leavitt graduated from Hopkins Academy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YBpBAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA151|title=History of the Hopkins Fund, Grammar School and Academy, in Hadley , Mass|first=Hopkins Academy (Hadley|last=Mass.)|date=October 3, 1890|publisher=Amherst record Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> which his brother Roger Hooker Leavitt attended as well.  The rest of his life he devoted to his substantial business affairs, handling his family's landholdings and serving in the town, county and state government. Leavitt eventually relocated to nearby Greenfield, where his uncle [[Jonathan Leavitt]] was a well-known judge. Hart Leavitt operated a store next door to his uncle Jonathan's law office. The store was the location for Greenfield's first newspaper and post office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://starrcenter.washcoll.edu/pdf/UGRR%20Guide%20Print.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609041234/http://starrcenter.washcoll.edu/pdf/UGRR%20Guide%20Print.pdf|url-status=dead|title=The Road to Freedom: Greenfield and the Underground Railroad, National Trust for Historic Preservation, Massachusetts Foundation for the Humanities, starrcenter.washcoll.edu|archivedate=June 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1835 Hart Leavitt, along with brothers Roger Hooker and Joshua, attended a state convention held in [[Utica, New York]], that was sponsored by the Utica Anti-Slavery Society. The convention's stated aim was to organize the [[New York Anti-Slavery Society]]. Hart Leavitt was one of a handful of delegates from outside New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oyJCAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA48|title=Proceedings of the New York Anti-slavery Convention, Held at Utica, October 21, and New York Anti-slavery State Society, Held at Peterboro', October 22, 1835|date=October 3, 1835|publisher=Printed at the Standard & Democrat office|via=Google Books}}</ref> The convention was marred by violence by pro-slavery factions. Hart Leavitt's brother was already a fervent abolitionist, and following graduation from [[Yale Law School]] and [[Yale Divinity School]], Rev. Joshua Leavitt had left both professions for the role of full-time editor of abolitionist and social reform publications including ''The Emancipator''.\n\nIn December 1836 the Franklin County Anti-Slavery was formed, tying together the strands of regional abolitionist sentiment. Merchant Hart Leavitt was a representative to the meeting. By 1840 Hart's father Roger was president of the Franklin County Anti-Slavery Society, and a co-founder with his son Joshua of the American & Foreign Anti-Slavery Society. That year Roger Leavitt, Hart's father, accepted the nomination of the newly formed Massachusetts Liberty Party to run for state Lieutenant Governor on an abolitionist ticket.<ref>Leavitt died the day after accepting the nomination.</ref> Hart Leavitt's mother Chloe had begun circulating a petition demanding the abolition of slavery in the [[District of Columbia]].\n\nHart Leavitt seems to have been increasingly politically active from the mid-1830s onward. By the late 1830 Hart Leavitt was using his Charlemont farm <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://home.nps.gov/ugrr/TEMPLATE/FrontEnd/Site3.CFM?SiteTerritoryID=129&ElementID=314|title=Hart and Mary Leavitt House, Charlemont, Massachusetts, Network to Freedom, National Park Service}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> as an Underground Railroad station, shuttling a succession of fugitive former slaves, the most prominent of whom was [[Basil Dorsey]], whom the Leavitt family (the three brothers and their father) sheltered and hid from pro-slavery forces. Dorsey lived with the family for over five years, during which time he apparently moved from one family home to another, hidden in plain sight.<ref>[http://www.florencehistoryproject.org/undergroundrailroad/florenceugrr.html Early Florence History and Underground Railroad Studies, The David Ruggles Center, florencehistoryproject.org]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Leavitt also sheltered other slaves on their way to Canada, and Leavitt's underground activities were extensive enough to prompt Ohio State University historian [[Wilbur Henry Siebert|Wilbur Siebert]] to list Leavitt as an operator of the Franklin County underground network, calling the merchant \"a sturdy abolitionist who did all he could to help slaves gain their freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://starrcenter.washcoll.edu/pdf/UGRR%20Guide%20Print.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609041234/http://starrcenter.washcoll.edu/pdf/UGRR%20Guide%20Print.pdf|url-status=dead|title=The Road to Freedom: Anti-Slavery Activity in Greenfield, Greenfield Human Rights Commission, starrcenter.washcoll.edu|archivedate=June 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHart Leavitt served as a Selectman for several years for the town of Heath,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.franklincountyhistory.com/heath/everts/04.html|title=Heath, Massachusetts -- 1879 -- Selectmen.|website=www.franklincountyhistory.com}}</ref> a member of the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lTc4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA589|title=Reports of controverted elections in the House of representatives: of the commonwealth of Massachusetts, from 1780 to 1852|first1=Massachusetts General Court House of|last1=Representatives|first2=Charles W.|last2=Storey|first3=Lewis|last3=Josselyn|date=October 3, 1853|publisher=White & Potter, printers to the state|via=Google Books}}</ref> as well as a Justice of the Peace and Franklin County Commissioner from Charlemont during his later life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MScDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA100|title=The Massachusetts Register and United States Calendar for the Year of Our Lord ...|date=October 3, 1853|publisher=Richardson, Lord & Holbrook, and James Loring|via=Google Books}}</ref> Hart Leavitt also served the town of Charlemont as a Selectman during the Civil War.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NgoTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA259|title=A History of Massachusetts in the Civil War|first=William|last=Schouler|date=October 3, 1871|publisher=E. P. Dutton & Company|via=Google Books}}</ref> He married in 1831 Mary Miller, daughter of Rev. Moses Miller of [[Heath, Massachusetts|Heath]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FxVAAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA58|title=Genealogical Record of the Dedham Branch of the Avery Family in America|first=Mrs Jane Greenough (Avery)|last=Carter|date=October 3, 1893|publisher=Press of Avery & Doten|via=Google Books}}</ref> The couple had six children: sons Edward Hart, Joseph Ware, Joshua, Roger, Spencer Miller; and daughter Mary. The home <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/archive/nebe/ugrr/massugrrjan.p65.pdf|title=Hart Leavitt House, Mass Network News, Volume Four, Number 1, January 2005, National Park Service, nps.gov}}</ref> of Hart and Mary Leavitt, located outside Charlemont, is listed on the National Park Service's Network to Freedom.<ref>Hart Leavitt also apparently lived for a time in a large home in Charlemont, which he subsequently sold to Allen Barnard of Boston.[http://www.memorialhall.mass.edu/collection/itempage.jsp?itemid=9375]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n*[[Joshua Leavitt]]\n*[[Roger Hooker Leavitt]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100609041234/http://starrcenter.washcoll.edu/pdf/UGRR%20Guide%20Print.pdf The Road to Freedom: Anti-Slavery Activity in Greenfield, Greenfield Human Rights Commission, the Greenfield Historical Commission, starrcenter.washcoll.edu]\n* [http://home.nps.gov/ugrr/TEMPLATE/FrontEnd/Site3.CFM?SiteTerritoryID=129&ElementID=314 Hart and Mary Leavitt House, Network to Freedom, National Park Service]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.florencehistoryproject.org/undergroundrailroad/florenceugrr.html Underground Railroad in Florence, Early Florence History and Underground Railroad Studies, The David Ruggles Center, florencehistoryproject.org]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leavitt, Hart}}\n[[Category:1809 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:Leavitt family]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:People of Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Heath, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:County commissioners in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Members of the Massachusetts House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:American abolitionists]]\n[[Category:Underground Railroad people]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Charlemont, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Undergroundrailroadsmall2.jpg|thumb|Map of some Underground Railroad routes]]\n'''Hart Leavitt''' (December 19, 1809 \u2013 1881) was a Massachusetts merchant, landowner, legislator and prominent abolitionist. Leavitt was the brother of [[Roger Hooker Leavitt]], with whom he operated an [[Underground Railroad]] station in [[Charlemont, Massachusetts]], where the two brothers, aided by a third sibling in New York, the reformer and abolitionist publisher [[Joshua Leavitt]], sheltered escaped slaves on their journey northward. The Massachusetts homes of Hart Leavitt and his brother Roger Hooker are both listed today on the [[National Park Service]]'s Underground Railroad Network to Freedom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/history/ugrr/list.htm|title=National Underground Railroad Network to Freedom Listings, National Park Service, nps.gov}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nHart Leavitt was born in [[Heath, Massachusetts]] in 1809, the son of landowner and Massachusetts legislator  Roger Leavitt <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxMXAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA339|title=History and Proceedings of the Pocumtuck Valley Memorial Association|first=Pocumtuck Valley Memorial Association (Deerfield|last=Mass.)|date=October 3, 1905|publisher=The Association|via=Google Books}}</ref> and his wife Chloe (Maxwell) Leavitt, and the grandson of Charlemont's first minister, [[Congregationalist]] Rev. [[Jonathan Leavitt (minister)|Jonathan Leavitt]], who was eventually turned out by the town for hi